  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_126512334" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/126512334" />
    <a title="Tom" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1358726-tom"><img alt="Tom" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1527887443p2/1358726.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/126512334?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom" href="/user/show/1358726-tom">Tom</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer126512334" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8144965528573865931">If you don&apos;t know much about poverty, this book may prove useful to you, but go in with eyes open. Shipler is at his best when he&apos;s letting the poor folks he speaks to speak for themselves. However, he is very much a liberal, and while he&apos;s talking with poor people we also get sympathetic interviews with bosses, managers, job trainers, &quot;tough love&quot; social workers, and the like. He praises people who shape themselves (and allow themselves to be shaped) into well-behaved, obedient workers set on c</span>
  <span id="freeText8144965528573865931" style="display:none">If you don't know much about poverty, this book may prove useful to you, but go in with eyes open. Shipler is at his best when he's letting the poor folks he speaks to speak for themselves. However, he is very much a liberal, and while he's talking with poor people we also get sympathetic interviews with bosses, managers, job trainers, "tough love" social workers, and the like. He praises people who shape themselves (and allow themselves to be shaped) into well-behaved, obedient workers set on climbing into higher levels of workplace hierarchy. His solution for the plight of the working poor is very much reformist and government-centered - the poor should overwhelm the rich at the voting booth, and his critique of how successful that has been/could be is nonexistent. The answer comes not from below - from poor people organizing themselves and building power - but from government programs, corporations, politicians, and benevolent gentry such as himself and his target audience. Capitalism needs to be changed, but is essentially good. It depends on poverty - Shipler says so quite uncritically - the issue for him is that the poor are treated better and given the opportunity to get ahead so others may replace them. If any of this made you cringe, you might be better off finding something with a little more teeth.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8144965528573865931" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


