    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2619009728" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2619009728" />
    <a title="Alyssa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/68591239-alyssa"><img alt="Alyssa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589481871p2/68591239.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2619009728?book_show_action=true">Dec 12, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alyssa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alyssa" href="/user/show/68591239-alyssa">Alyssa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/68591239-alyssa?shelf=common-read">common-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2619009728" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10552050885693954206">A fascinating read. I probably never would have picked it up if it weren&apos;t for work, but Shipler does a great job of humanizing the individuals he interviews without pitying them or setting them up as martyrs. There was a lot more narrative than I expected from this kind of non-fiction, but I was really drawn into each person&apos;s story. <br/><br/>I would be interested to hear more of his opinions on the current state of the working poor, since the book was originally published in 2004 and edited in 2016.</span>
  <span id="freeText10552050885693954206" style="display:none">A fascinating read. I probably never would have picked it up if it weren't for work, but Shipler does a great job of humanizing the individuals he interviews without pitying them or setting them up as martyrs. There was a lot more narrative than I expected from this kind of non-fiction, but I was really drawn into each person's story. <br /><br />I would be interested to hear more of his opinions on the current state of the working poor, since the book was originally published in 2004 and edited in 2016.</span>
