    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1069254600" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1069254600" />
    <a title="Jennifer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7716395-jennifer"><img alt="Jennifer" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1069254600?book_show_action=true">Oct 01, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jennifer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jennifer" href="/user/show/7716395-jennifer">Jennifer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7716395-jennifer?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7716395-jennifer?shelf=banned-books">banned-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1069254600" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17435720775925633490">I decided to read this book because it appeared on a list of books that parents wanted banned from a high school reading list since it was &quot;critical of capitalism&quot;. Those parents did not actually read this book. What this book is critical of is this: the wealthiest nation in the world cannot find the will to take a holistic, comprehensive, programmatic view of addressing the numerous causes of poverty so that individuals who are standing on the line between poor and destitute can find a way out </span>
  <span id="freeText17435720775925633490" style="display:none">I decided to read this book because it appeared on a list of books that parents wanted banned from a high school reading list since it was "critical of capitalism". Those parents did not actually read this book. What this book is critical of is this: the wealthiest nation in the world cannot find the will to take a holistic, comprehensive, programmatic view of addressing the numerous causes of poverty so that individuals who are standing on the line between poor and destitute can find a way out to the middle class.<br /><br />Instead of blaming the system or the individual, he points out that people are on a spectrum- each person has some personal blame, and some blame rests with "the system"- low wages, government bureaucracy, poor schools, inability to find decent housing and/or dependable transportation, utter lack of access to decent medical treatment. In addition, he makes a case that strong kinship ties-family or community-can mitigate some of these circumstances, if you are lucky enough to have that asset. Many of the people profiled in this book did not. He shows very well how these problems are all woven together, and how one crisis or one bad choice can cause a cascading effect of problems when you do not have the health, the money, the family support, the community, or the job security to manage.<br /><br />In order to find solutions, therefore, you cannot take just one issue- housing, employment or medical care, for example, and attempt to make that the "solution to poverty". If you believe that this is an issue that government should leave to churches, charities and non-profits, he points out how many of the issues can be traced right back to laws and government policy. In addition, no one church, no one charity, no one non-profit is equipped to deal comprehensively with the problems some of these people face. Chasing a program here and a program there can become a full time job in itself. However, he does not advocate government taking over entirely- there is a role for the private sector, for the non-profit sector, for charitable organizations and for churches as well- and there is also the requirement for people to take personal responsibility for their own actions and decisions. He calls, in the conclusion, for political opponents to "cross into each other's territory to pick up solutions from the opposing side". Unfortunately, that likely won't be happening anytime soon.<br /><br />Instead of banning this book, this book should be on the reading list of every social studies class in America. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17435720775925633490" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

