    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_45459297" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/45459297" />
    <a title="Bookmarks Magazine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1008236-bookmarks-magazine"><img alt="Bookmarks Magazine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1233856382p2/1008236.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/45459297?book_show_action=true">Feb 05, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bookmarks Magazine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bookmarks Magazine" href="/user/show/1008236-bookmarks-magazine">Bookmarks Magazine</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780375408908" href="/book/show/441271.The_Working_Poor">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer45459297" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15938538152035744717"><p>&quot;Nobody who works hard should be poor in America,&quot; writes Pulitzer Prize-winning author Shipler. Few would disagree with that statement, yet even fewer would agree on how to reduce the factors that cause poverty in America. Presenting individual case studies, Shipler exposes the vicious social and economic injustices that define the working poor. (How can you buy false teeth if you don&apos;t have a job? But how can you get a job without teeth?) At times, he lets his frustration get the better of him</p></span>
  <span id="freeText15938538152035744717" style="display:none"><p>"Nobody who works hard should be poor in America," writes Pulitzer Prize-winning author Shipler. Few would disagree with that statement, yet even fewer would agree on how to reduce the factors that cause poverty in America. Presenting individual case studies, Shipler exposes the vicious social and economic injustices that define the working poor. (How can you buy false teeth if you don't have a job? But how can you get a job without teeth?) At times, he lets his frustration get the better of him, and makes sweeping judgements about single mothers, divorce, and race--even though the racially diverse cast we'd expect is largely absent. And since his reforms are convincing but uncontroversial, we're not left with much but despair. But if <i>Working Poor</i> lacks some long-range vision, it "begs our attention. Read it and be ashamed" (<i>San Diego Union-Tribune</i>). </p><p>This is an excerpt from a review published in <a href="http://www.bookmarksmagazine.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Bookmarks magazine</a>.</p></span>
  <a data-text-id="15938538152035744717" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

